history.content:
The class is going to be on "Advance Cryptography" Fridays 1-4pm still in 405 Soda (Somehow the title has not been updated in the draft). 
This class will be about various "recent" topics in cryptography. Each class is 3 hrs long and will be about going through one or two of the recent important/interest papers in detail. The exact selection of papers has not been decided yet but it will be based on topics related to secure computation (with an emphasis on garbling techniques), fully-homomorphic encryption and obfuscation. The goal is to help grad students more aware of the important open problems (especially ones which might be within reach).
Prereqs: There are no specific prereqs except for some prior familiarity with cryptography (or you can try catching that up on your own; this may take a fair bit of your time). Otherwise, you may not benefit much from this class. However, if you are hoping for a first graduate-level crypto class then I would suggest CS276. I will teach that in Fall 18.

Does anyone know what this will be about (besides "Advanced Cryptography")?  I'm guessing this is similar to the CS194 he was offering last semester but then canceled -- is there a reason why this is listed as a 294 this semester?
